Introduction¶

A Central Processing Unit (CPU) is the heart of the computer that performs many processing functions for the system. CPUs are built by placing billions of microscopic transistors onto a single computer chip. Those transistors allow it to make the calculations it needs to run programs that are stored on your systems memory. CPUs can also have multiple cores, which recieve instructions and perform operations to satisy those instructions. One of the most common advancements of CPU technology is in making those transistors smaller and increasing the number of cores. This has resulted in the steady improvement to CPU speed over the decades, often referred to as Moores Law.

The importance and value of advancing CPUs introduces great competition in the field of CPU development. In this project, we analyze the progression of CPU processing power in regards to its price to performance ratio, whether it is above or below the expected performance compared to the prediction of Moore's law, and the average marketshare of each competitor in relation to the strength of their products.

Getting CPU and GPU Data¶

Using the requests library, we can get and create a dataframe to store the product deatails and information of each CPU. We created a dataframe with all the necessary columns and added the CPU data from Techpowerup.com to it. We parsed techpowerup.com using BeautifulSoup and further simplified the html by identifing and filtering the data from where it is stored in a table. This was done first for the year 2000 and then continued to the year 2023. We then cleaned up the table by getting rid of blank columns. Additionally, we had to include a 5 second sleep timer because the target website was giving us an error for too many requests if we didn't wait.

Source: https://www.techpowerup.com/cpu-specs/

In [2]:
def getdata(url,kind):
    if kind=='cpu':
        columns=['Name','Codename','Cores','Clock','Socket','Process','L3 Cache','TDP','Released']
    elif kind=='gpu':
        columns=['Product Name','GPU Chip','Release Date','Bus','Memory','GPU Clock','Memory Clock','Shaders/TMUs/ROPs']
           
    df=pd.DataFrame()
    rest='&sort=released'
    r=requests.get(url+str(2000)+rest)
    root = BeautifulSoup(r.text, 'html')
    table = root.find_all("table")
    
    if kind=='cpu':
        other=pd.read_html(str(table))[0]
    elif kind=='gpu':
        other=pd.read_html(str(table[1]))[0]
        
    df=other
    if kind=='cpu':
        df = df.iloc[: , :-1]
    df = df.set_axis(columns, axis=1)

    years=[]
    for i in range(2001,2023):
        r=requests.get(url+str(i)+rest)
        root = BeautifulSoup(r.text, 'html')
        table = root.find_all("table")
        
        if kind=='cpu':
            other = pd.read_html(str(table))[0]
        elif kind=='gpu':
            other=pd.read_html(str(table[1]))[0]
        
        if kind=='cpu':
            other = other.iloc[: , :-1]
        other = other.set_axis(columns, axis=1)
        df=pd.concat([df,other])
        time.sleep(5)
    return df

The below cell just runs the function above to get all the data. We print our progress from 2000 to 2023 so we know how much we have loaded so far.

Adding Performance Measurements to the Data¶

We then got performance data for each of the CPUs from CPUBenchmark.net. These performance numbers are from benchmarks ran by CPUBenchmark that executes complex mathematical calcuations involving compression, encryption, and physics simulations. The higher the performance number the faster the CPU is. Once again, we created a dataframe with the columns we wanted and used BeautifulSoup to parse through the webpages HTML. Unforunately, the data was not in a table this time so we had to split up the unordered list it was in by line and remove any extra blank rows. We also used the chain module to flatten our data into a one-dimensional array. We then merged the two dataframes into one by using a library function that matched the names of one dataframe to the closesnt match in the other.

Source for CPU performance data: https://www.cpubenchmark.net/

In [6]:
from itertools import chain

columnNames=['Name','Percentage','Performance','Price']
df2=pd.DataFrame(columns = columnNames)
url= "https://www.cpubenchmark.net/"
types = ["high_end_cpus", "mid_range_cpus", "midlow_range_cpus", "low_end_cpus"]
# types = ["high_end_cpus"]
data_list = []

for cpu_type in types:
    r=requests.get(url + str(cpu_type) + ".html")
    root = BeautifulSoup(r.text, 'html')
    root.prettify() # up to here is just getting all the html
    
    table = root.find_all("ul") # this gets all the unordered lists on the page 
    table = table[12] # The 13th unordered list which is the main table
    table = str(table.text)
    data_list.append(table.split("\n")[1:-1])
    
flatten_list = list(chain.from_iterable(data_list))

import difflib 

names=[]
percentage=[]
performance=[]
price=[]
for item in flatten_list:
    result = re.search(r"((.)+)(\(\d+%\))([\d|,]+)(\$[\d|.|,]+|NA)", item)
    names.append(result.group(1))
    percentage.append(result.group(3))
    performance.append(result.group(4))
    price.append(result.group(5))
df2['Name']=names
df2['Percentage']=percentage
df2['Performance']=performance
df2['Price']=price

df2['Name'] = df2['Name'].apply(lambda x: (difflib.get_close_matches(x, cpu_df['Name'])[:1] or [None])[0])
cpu_df = cpu_df.merge(df2)

Cleaning the Data¶

In cleaning our data we first get rid of rows which had unknown release dates or were never released and rows where the price of the CPU is not known. We then converted the rest of the release dates into datetime objects depending on the format of their date (Ex: 12/20 or 2020 or 12/15/2021). The datatime objects make the dates uniform in type and make it easier to work with when graphing later.

In [11]:
from datetime import date
from datetime import datetime
In [12]:
cpu_df = cpu_df[cpu_df.Price != 'NA']
In [13]:
cpu_df = cpu_df[cpu_df['Released'] != 'Never Released']
cpu_df = cpu_df[cpu_df['Released'] != 'Unknown']
dates=[]
for i,row in cpu_df.iterrows():
    row['Released'] = row['Released'].replace('st', '').replace('rd', '').replace('nd', '').replace('th', '')
    if len(row['Released'])==8:
        dt_obj = datetime.strptime(row['Released'], '%b %Y')
    elif len(row['Released'])==4:
        dt_obj = datetime.strptime(row['Released'], '%Y')
    else:
        dt_obj = datetime.strptime(row['Released'], '%b %d, %Y')
    dates.append(dt_obj.date())
cpu_df['datetime_Released']=dates

We then used a regex statement to simplify data on cores/threads into just the cores (which is what we are looking at). We added the number of actual cores to a new column in the dataframe named "Actual Cores."* and years from the Datetime objects to a column named "Year Relased". We did years here because Moore's law estimates the data in 2 year intervals.

In [14]:
cores=[]
for i,row in cpu_df.iterrows():
    if len(row['Cores'])==1 or len(row['Cores'])==2:
        result = re.search(r"(\d+)", row['Cores'])
    else:
        result = re.search(r"(\d+) \/ (\d+)|(\d+)", row['Cores'])
    cores.append(result.group(1))
cpu_df['Actual Cores']=cores
cpu_df['Actual Cores']=cpu_df['Actual Cores'].astype(float)
In [15]:

cpu_df['Year_Released']=years

Finally we need to clean the Performance and Price columns in our dataframe to be easily plotted later.

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
def plotcpus(startyear,endyear,plottype,xtype,ytype):
    temp=cpu_df
    plt.figure(figsize = (13,5))
    if xtype=='Year_Released':
        temp=cpu_df[cpu_df[xtype]==startyear]
        for i in range(startyear+1,endyear+1):
            temp=pd.concat([temp,cpu_df[cpu_df[xtype]==i]])
    if plottype=='scatter':
        sns.scatterplot(x=xtype, y=ytype, data=temp)
    elif plottype=='violin':
            sns.violinplot(x=xtype, y=ytype, data=temp,scale='width')

Out[25]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Exponential Regression for Performance of CPUs over Time')

We now look at the actual function representation of the growth of CPU performance over time using our data. We used the polyfit function while using the log function on the y-values, the performance numbers, to get the accurate coefficients for our exponential regression. We now need to use some simple algebra to take Euler's number and raise it to the coeffcients. With this we get our exponential regression function which is estmiated to be closely related to the y=1.2^x function. This doesn't exactly match Moore's law function of doubling every two years, but it still has the exponetial performance growth that we want and expect to see. We can also now somewhat accurately predict how CPU performance is going to be in the near future with this function. CPU performance is going to be around 80000 when nearing 2030.

A Look At How Market Competition Affects the Performance of New CPUs¶

In [29]:
def getmarketshare(desktop):
    url = 'https://www.cpubenchmark.net/market_share.html'
    response = requests.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text,'lxml')
    if desktop:
        script_tag = soup.findAll('script')[15]
    else:
        script_tag = soup.findAll('script')[14]     
    data=str(script_tag)
    pattern = re.compile(r'([\d+,[\d+|.]+\])')
    records = pattern.findall(data)

    intelshare=[]
    amdshare=[]
    index=0
    for i in records:
        match = re.search(r'\[(\d+),([\d+|.]+)\]',i)
        if index < 74:
            intelshare.append(float(match.group(2)))
        else:
            amdshare.append(float(match.group(2)))
        index+=1
    return intelshare,amdshare

def plotmarketshare(intel,amd):
    years=[]
    ticks=[]
    years=np.linspace(2004,2022,74)
    fig, ax_left = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,8))
    ax_right = ax_left.twinx()
    plt.locator_params(axis='x', nbins=20)
    ax_left.plot(years,intel)
    ax_left.plot(years,amd,color='red')
    ax.set_ylabel('Market Share %')
    ax.set_xlabel('Year')
    return ax_left, ax_right

Intel was dominating the CPU marketspace for decades, leaving AMD in the dust in terms of marketshare. With essentially no threatening competition, Intel wasn't pushed to create CPUS to outperform someone else. However, in 2017, AMD release a new line of "Ryzen" chips which outperformed many of Intels current chips. This reignition of competition lead to a new CPU war in which the performance of CPUs was drastically affected.

Below, we will use market share data over the years and compare it to the changes in processing power from our calculations above and see how this competition benefit advancements in CPUs as a whole.

Source for marketshare data: https://www.cpubenchmark.net/market_share.html

Hypothesis Testing¶

In [33]:
import statsmodels.api as sm
from scipy import stats

Now we want to test our hypothesis to see if CPU performance actually coincides with Moore's law. The null hypothesis for our test is that CPU performance does not grow exponentially over time. We will be using our model and the statsmodels package to calculate our p-value and the coefficient of determination, R^2. To reject our null hypothesis, we are looking for a p-value of less than 0.05. We are also going to look for a R^2 value as it tells us how well our model fits the data. The closer the R^2 value is to 1 the better our model fits the data.

As seen from the results, we have a p-value of less than 0.05. We actually got a p-value of 0.0, so we can confidently reject the null hypothesis of processor performance not growing exponentially over time.

Now taking a look at the R^2 value, we see it has a value of 0.669. Having a high R^2 model means that the model fits your data. The closer to 1 it is the better your model. Our model isn't exactly close to 1. This is supported by the fact that we got a function for performance over time of y=1.2^x earlier. This is most likely due to the high variance of CPU performance when AMD started releasing their Ryzen CPUs around 2017. During this time we see a huge jump in performance across the board. This made our model inaccurate because it did most of its values came from 2000 to 2016 where CPU performance wasn't increasing that much.

To lower our residuals we would want to weigh the values from 2017 onwards more in our model so that it can have more accurate predicted performance numbers.

The Takeaway¶

After analyzing the CPU performance and cost over time we have learned quite a few things. The most important thing we have seen is that the performance of CPUs does have a somewhat exponetial growth that is closely related to Moore's Law. Although it doesn't exactly match Moores Law of doubling performance every two years(a function that is similar to y=2^x), we do get a closely matched function of y=1.2^x. Moore's law also states that the cost of compute power should be halved. From our analysis, we see that the cost and the cost to performance of processors have been relatively the same throughout time. This heavily is due to things such as inflation, but just by looking at the numbers this part of Moore's law doesn't seem to coincide with reality. Lastly, we have found that market competition, mainly between AMD and Intel, has a huge impact on the increase in performance for processors. As seen from our analysis, the increase in performance of processors saw exponential growth after AMD came out with their new Ryzen series processors that was made to combat Intel who has controlled most of the CPU market during the past decade.

Market competition is important for technological advancements, so we hope to see more of that to get more powerful and more efficient processors in the future.

Improvements¶

The main thing we would want to improve upon is our exponetial regression function to get it closer to a funciton that is doubling every two years(similar to y=2^x). The improvements we would make to our model would be to put more weight on the performance values starting from 2017 because that is when we actually start to see exponetial growth in performance for processors.
